          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Pheochromocytoma.</span></span></span></span></p>"
        }
      ],
      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">An 8-year-old child from a rural area is brought to the pediatric department with symptoms of vomiting, sunken eyes, reduced skin turgor, lethargy, salt craving, and hyperpigmentation of the skin. The child&#39;s blood pressure is measured at 100/60mmHg, with a random blood sugar (RBS) level of 60mg/dl. Laboratory tests reveal a serum sodium level of 110 mEq/L and a serum potassium level of 6.0 mEq/L. Based on the provided information, what is the most likely diagnosis?</span></span></span></span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q6641916",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 32835,
